Â @FILMBRIGHTÂ  Whilst the fisheries' scientists, and the Marine Stewardship Council are still in a frenzy to dispute the amazing insight Seaspiracy has given us, I find it stunning that the MSC were given opportunity after opportunity to meet with Ali and Lucy. Time and again they were both turned away. A relative of mine, and a very experienced diver, told me how his diving buddy was almost killed himself when he became entangled in ghost fishing nets in the ocean. He lived because the divers he dived with, risked their own lives to saving him. And yet, this is what the commercial fishing industry is doing every day to our marine wildlife, plants and ocean corals. We really have to do all we can to support Seaspiracy in this mission, the negligence and total lack of regulation for what is happening in our seas is shocking, not to mention the slavery, and starvation of West Africa whose fish are taken illegally while the true inhabitants face poverty and starvation. Â @aureliusVAÂ  No one lied on the documentary - the statistic of 2048 was created by the fishing industry experts themselves.  Google Jacobin Seaspiracy, watch Sir David Attenborough's 2020 A Life On This Planet.  Sir David Attenborough is a highly respected nature biographer, does that mean he is telling untruths too?  I think not.  Whether you agree with each statistic is your perogative, but the ultimate devastation is all of our concern.  How can we agree to bottom trawling nets that obliterate all fish wildlife and the plants and corals at the bottom of our ocean beds???  A friend of mine was only telling me today how is diving buddy almost died when he too became entangled in ghost fishing nets.  This is what we are doing to our marine life every day.

Â @aureliusVAÂ  Whilst the fisheries' scientists, and the Marine Stewardship Council are still in a frenzy to dispute the amazing insight Seaspiracy has given us, I find it stunning that the MSC were given opportunity after opportunity to meet with Ali and Lucy. Time and again they were both turned away. A relative of mine, and a very experienced diver, told me how his diving buddy was almost killed himself when he became entangled in ghost fishing nets in the ocean. He lived because the divers he dived with, risked their own lives to saving him. And yet, this is what the commercial fishing industry is doing every day to our marine wildlife, plants and ocean corals. We really have to do all we can to support Seaspiracy in this mission, the negligence and total lack of regulation for what is happening in our seas is shocking, not to mention the slavery, and starvation of West Africa whose fish are taken illegally while the true inhabitants face poverty and starvation. If you have not seen it, watch the update - fished illegally to be sold back to the true naturals who are now in very dire straits.

This is a typical Netflix doc in the same style as Tiger King. YES, it touches on a few hugely important issues (human rights, animal welfare, illegal fishing, unsustainable practices, waste) but oversimplifies the overall issue to such an extent it loses it's impact. Simply 'leaving the ocean alone' would condemn millions of the worlds poorest and most vulnerable to starvation (and what about indigenous access and cultural preservation?). This is a massively complicated issue, and the glaring question left is how the doc makers propose to make up the food lost from the sea from production on land with the same or less environmental impact. An interesting doc, but if you're really interested in this, seek out what ocean scientists have to say about it.

As a vegetarian going vegan, there are inaccuracies in this documentaries. 

1.) Fish being gone by 2048 was based on a 2006 research paper that has since then have been found not accurate by later studies. The researchers did not intentionally mislead people with their study, they just used the wrong metric. 

2.) MSC is paid off by the fishing industry. This part is a bit fishy. MSC claims that their certifications are carried out by accredited 3rd party bodies. However, you can still get the certification even if you use long line fishing and trawling, which is known to be destructive to sea animals and coral reefs. It seems like MSC's bar is set fairly low that most fisheries can get the certifications. Ineligible fisheries are ones that use poison or explosives to fish, slaves, shark fin violation, etc. 

3.) Some of the people interview have later claimed that their interview was taken out of context. Christina Hicks doesn't give too much information after her initial tweet. 

4.) Seaspiracy highlights Japanese and Chinese fisheries as well as Thai ones too. These are the worst in the industry. USA, Norway, and other European countries are much better regulated in comparison. Their points aren't wrong, but they are taking the worst fisheries to represent a whole. 

After making these points, I'm still not going to eat fish since, by catch of dolphins, over fishing, environmental impact of fish farms, trawling killing environment, etc are all real issues portrayed accurately in this film.

It's obviously a very important issue and we need to reduce fishing by regulation on the UN level. 

But come on, this is a pretty bad documentary. The guy is way too aggressive about his ways, and any time he has an interview he obviously cuts and edits to make it seem like he's getting the responses he wants. 
One interviewee says "My associate can't have said to eliminate fish", the guy says she did, she says "no, there is no way she said to ELIMINATE FISH", then he cuts to her saying to "eliminate or reduce your intake of fish", which is a completely different thing. The documentary then leaves it as that, as if they made a point or something. The interview itself becomes completely irrelevant and any useful information that could have been gotten out of it is lost. 
He "sneaks up" on a fishery and HAPPENS to discover that it's a big tuna fishery. As if that information is not readily available on google. 

The documentary should have focused more on the facts that fishing gear is the greatest part of plastics in the oceans, that dolphins are being killed in attempts to increase the number of fish in the sea, that overfishing is a huge issue.... But instead it's just a cringe worthy attempt at creating "action" out of nothing. 

I hope other higher quality documentaries are made on this issue.

Â @S. F.Â  the problem is, as this documentary clearly shows, the â€˜sustainableâ€™ labelled fish is very often not sustainable.

Itâ€™s propaganda, and not even well-done propaganda. If the filmmakers werenâ€™t so busy misleading and manipulating their audience, they couldâ€™ve actually made good points for a greener and more sustainable future. As it stands though, this trash has zero credibility and belongs in the same  garbage bin as Zeitgeist and Loose Change.
Â @Curtis006Â  Whatâ€™s so wrong about it? Theyâ€™re pointing out multiple flaws within the industry. Care to elaborate?
Â @Curtis006Â  If it's so flawed then why can't you provide a single point of criticism?

Â @LinkÂ  where to even begin? The film (I wonâ€™t call it a â€œdocumentaryâ€) is nothing more than a propaganda piece for veganism, as are the directorâ€™s previous two films Iâ€™ve since found out. I havenâ€™t seen these previous two films, but it seems as though they have the exact same faults, and have been called out as such, from what Iâ€™ve read. It blatantly and obviously twists facts and selectively edits its interviews with leading questions to suit the narrative it already pre-determined, and does so shamelessly. It engages constantly in this hackneyed sensationalism and overdramatization. You could almost watch it as a parody. There were moments that were so obviously staged and being sold by the director so poorly that for a moment I questioned whether it was all a Netflix April foolâ€™s joke. There are, no doubt, a lot of problems in this industry. And I actually agree with the filmâ€™s main concluding thesis: that a social shift towards eating less meat, including fish, collectively, would be of tremendous benefit to the environment and our future. But I fear this film is such an embarrassment that it will hinder that goal rather than help it for years to come. You canâ€™t get to the world you want by lying and tricking people. Any vegan or environmental activist, if theyâ€™re smart or even just self-aware, should be distancing themselves from this trash as much as possible.
Â @Rappa KaljaÂ  I invite you to read my previous post.

Â @Curtis006Â  You said nothing of substance, you just complained that they "dramatized" it. The stats may have been incorrect in some cases, but it is also not possible to know whether stats are truly correct. As a meat and fish eater I fully agree with the message of this documentary and plan on switching to veganism. It is pure hypocrisy to claim to care about the planet and people while arrogantly dismissing this documentary just cause it promotes veganism ?? How ridiculous. Veganism obviously does good for the environment and people. The sole complaint I saw from "experts" is that this documentary tells everyone to stop eating fish and it's not thinking about the poor. This is wrong because it clearly showed how indeginous African populations are struggling to eat and find fish because of commercial and illegal fishing, both markets are heavily unregulated and in fact impossible to regulate as you cannot control what happens at sea. This documentary was directed at an audience that isvprivileged enough to afford a Netflix membership and the devices to watch it, they sure as hell can stop consuming commercial fish.

Â @SarahÂ  indigenous African populations struggle to eat and find fish because they themselves use illigal fishing methods and do not adhere to maximum sustainable yield levels set by fishing institutes. In general small-scale fishing is more dangerous to fish than large-scale fishing if you balance out the amount of fish caught

Â @Kees StijneÂ  What nonsense you are spewing. Since when catching some fishes to eat is less sustainable than anything else ? You're blaming a few people trying to eat instead of the obvious large numbers of industrial and illegal boats coming there, that you can literally see on footage and images pillaging Africa' vital resources, but whatever fits your narrative

Â @SarahÂ  It is by method of how these fish are caught. Large boats can be regulated but individual fishermen going into lakes and using poisons and nets with small mesh sizes cannot.Â Ofcource 1 fishermen will not do nearly as much damage as a large boat, but if you compare a ton fished through large-scale compared to 1 ton fished through individuals, the small-scale will in general be much more damaging

Â @Kees StijneÂ   Oh my Lord. These industrial boats couldn't be further from regulated and you can literally see on footage these boats catching A LOT of fish and dumping many unwanted dead ones back into the ocean. It's not sustainable at all. It's pure greed for money.

What I'm trying to say is that I agree with Curtis, there are many issues that we need to tackle in the world of seafood production. But a documentary based on people taken out of context and non-truths does more harm than good to the goal of sustainable seafood (which does indeed exist). Many experts on this subject (university professors, certification NGO's, ecologists) have spoken out against this film. And don't claim that large seafood has the whole world bribed, I'm a marine bioloFist and have not seen any money. Maybe it's large vegetable industry that has this producer in their pocket...

Â @SarahÂ  and how do you think it happens with individual fishermen? This dumping of bycatch is not allowed in the EU for example. Nobody wants bycatch but there are rules, especially for certification, that try to prevent this from happening. It's a difficult industry, so is all of agriculture, but criticizing NGO'S that try to improve this is not beneficial. I can guarantee you that they ship is not MSC certified. 

Primary production in all sectors is a messy industry, and has a long way to go for sustainability but blanketing an entire industry as "bad" is not a good way to promote a healthy future.

Â @Kees StijneÂ  You are literally dismissing so many things with pure dishonesty. With sustainable fishing you are ultimately still killing more, no matter how nice you paint it to be. It is also inherently cruel towards fishes and other sea animals who are proven to feel pain and fear. You might as well call it "sustainable slaughtering", these two words are oxymorons. This documentary takes a standpoint where it takes into account the actual pain and cruelty inflicted on animals, and that's totally valid. You could hear the whales screaming in pain when getting killed. If you don't care, just admit it instead of portraying this documentary as terribly dangerous when it fact veganism is the least harmful thing for the planet and the beings living in it. And please, these EU regulations are meaningless, they cannot and don't control what happens at sea. These labels are all for show and profit, anyone with half a brain knows that.

Â @SarahÂ  I care a lot for animals, but the world you paint is black and white. These labels are not for show and profits for the organization that runs them is literally a non-profit organization. You have to start somewhere with sustainability, and veganism is a great place to do so. But veganism is in it self not sustainable, at least not for the vast majority of the world who cannot afford it. But anything taken out of context can be cruel to animals or people alike. Slavery also exists in coffee and chocolate, deforestation for soy and advocado, even the killing of millions of rats and mice to keep grain silos pest free. Does this mean that we should stop eating those products? No, we have to try and find products made in a sustainable fashion. The same is true for seafood and animal production. I am not advocating that there is not a lot wrong in the industry, but punishing those that try to make a difference is counterproductive.

Look at what positives the seafood industry has done, it has transformed one of the poorest states in Vietnam to one of the richest. It has provided micronutrients to the malnourished people of South-Sudan. Lionfish hunting is saving the reefs of Bonaire. When care is taken, the industry can get results for a brighter future, but when left unchecked can do devastating damage. 

Agriculture and fishing is a very difficult industry to understand and regulate. Most people have no idea how it works and thus criticism is easily done, but few offer actual solutions. And those that do should not be burned by a film such as this.

Â @Kees StijneÂ  It's so naive of you to think that non-profits are honest, there's so much corruption out there and in case you didn't notice some of these organization  in the documentary have been literally created and funded by corporations running the fishing industry. It's a very common practice in all industries, not just in fishing, to create organizations and bribe audits and certification providers in order to validate their clearly unethical practices. And I don't know about you but I never heard a vegetable scream in pain while being peeled and cut. There's a lot of unfair practices regarding the vegetables and fruits industries but it is not hard to get around that by buying local which is often far cheaper, and growing your own veggies too. However fishing will always remain an obscure and cruel industry no matter how ethical you try to make it,  animals are suffering regardless. Also transparency in terms of the vegan industry is far easier to have, but when it comes to the fishing industry, you simply cannot know what goes on at sea. And after seeing the unnecessary mass slaughter of sea animals, slavery and indigenous populations being deprived of their own resources, I don't think this industry should be supported any longer, that's what this documentary literally advocates for and it is absolutely correct in my view.

Â @SarahÂ  so the laws of the government don't work, NGO'S are corrupt and allow for evil cooperations to continue operating under the pretense of sustainability and indigenous people are innocent and know exactly how to manage their own resources? What about the UN's standard development goals? 

You can call me naive all you want but you are starting to sound like a conspiracy theorist... All the experts out there are advocating for change in the seafood industry, me included, but this film does not do the change that has already happened and the people fighting for a better future justice. It is a simple shock factor aimed to get money by getting naive people who have no knowledge of this industry to watch it. And it succeeds at that.

Â @Kees StijneÂ  A conspiracy theorist ? It's really not my fault if you don't have awareness of what goes on in the world and what governments, businesses and people in general are capable of doing for money. All these big organizations backed and funded by governments "helping" Africa and poorer countries are completely overlooking the ongoing plundering and theft of Africa's resources, as well as Western countries' complicit implications in these affairs. And they are going to keep overlooking these problems because it is simply in their own interest to do so. You need to think for yourself and use of your own judgement. I'm not saying to deny science and facts, I'm saying be mindful with who communicates the facts, how they do it and what possible biases and interests they may have when doing so. And regardless of how sustainable "sustainable fishing" is, it is still cruel and doesn't take away the pain for animals. It's hypocritical and messed up to claim to care a lot about animals yet be fine with killing them.

Â @SarahÂ  â€œYou need to think for yourself and use your own judgement. Iâ€™m not saying to deny science and facts, Iâ€™m saying be mindful with who communicates the facts, how they do it and what possible biases and interests they may have when doing soâ€. 

^ you really need to follow your own advice, Sarah. Seeing the obvious faults in a movie such as â€œSeaspiracyâ€ is like a beginnerâ€™s lesson in this regard.

Â @Curtis006Â   It's shallow and arrogant to dismiss a whole documentary that shows some erroneous stats when the overall message remains just. The damage of fishing is present and visible to anyone who goes near or at the sea.
Â @SarahÂ  itâ€™s just and good to not only dismiss but actively scorn a piece of propaganda that causes more harm than good. Seaspiracy is just that.
